{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930102501/0581.xml":{"full_text":"40th Anniversary\nWe are 40 years old, but\nhave forgotten to mention\nit because we have been\nbusy. This is the oldest fire\nproof depository in the\nUnited States, and our\nfriends give us a very good\nreputation. Quite a number\nof our staff have been here\nsince the early days. We\nare still learning.\nflfrUPity,\n1140 FIFTEENTH ST\nA SAfE DEPOSITORY FOR 36 YEAPS\nCA.ASPINWAUL. PRESIDENT\nIrrflkJ\nTwo quiet corner apartments; all\nrooms outside; continuous telephone\nand elevator service; automatic\nheating, hot-water and refrigeration.\nSeasonable rentals.\nCOPLEY COURTS\n1514 17th Street N.W.\nRegular Delivery\nOver 100,000 families read The\nStar every day. The great ma\njority have the paper delivered\nregularly every evening and Sun\nday morning at a cost of U 4\ncents daily and 5 cents Sunday.\nIf you are not taking advan\ntage of this regular service at\nthis low cost, telephone National\n5000 now and service will start\ntomorrow.\n2001 16th St. N.W.\n3 Rooms, Kitchen\nand Bath\nELECTRIC REFRIGERATION\nFINE CORNER I\nStore for Sale\nSoutheast corner Rock Creek I\n1 Church road and Georgia ave- I\nI nue. Immediate occupancy. I\nI Building can be remodeled to I\nH include 1,800 sq. ft. of floor I\napace.\n2nd Floor Income, SIOO\nFor Month\nPRICED TO SELL\n(Exclusive Agents)\n1415 K St. N.W.\nNa. 4750\nNo Trades \u2014No SI,OOO\nPayment\nI 4303 16th St.\nI N.W. I\nI *37,500\nWe offer the best value on\n1 16th Bt. today, and because of\nIt the very unusual price we must\nI insist on a substantial cash\nII payment. Your broker, lawyer or\nH banker will advise you that this\nU is a true value. Drive out any\ntime and inspect this beautiful\nH comer brick, with 10 rooms and\nH 3 baths, oil heat, two-car garage.\nOpen and Lighted Day\nand Night\nPhillips Canby, Inc.\n>Mlt.r\u2014Exclusive Ascot\nInvestment Building\nNational 4600\nUssss\u00dfsssssssssssssssssssssssssdi\nSPECIAL NOTICES.\n23x55 VAN UN*, MOTOR VAN rST\nmov.il anywhere. \u201cPool'' vans for ihlp\nm.nts of small lots to' and from New York\nSECURITY STORAGE COMPANY. 1140 Fif\nteenth street. Decatur 0443.\nON AND AFTER THI3 DAT* t wILL NOT\nbe responsible for any debts contracted by\nany other than myself. W. A. SHANNON,\n6718 2nd st. n.w. 37*\nFOR YOUR HALLOWEEN PARTY.\nHILDICKS SWEET APPLE JUICE.\nAt Your Dealer's.\nOr Phone\nSAMUEL C. PALMER CO.,\nWest 01S0.\n(tiaras FOR RENT. SUITABLE FOR\nBRIDGE PARTIES, baneuets, weddlnts and\nmeetings. 10c up per day each; new chairs.\nUNITED STATES STORAGE CO., 118 10th\nSt. n.w. Metropolitan 1844.\nIP YOUR FINANCIAL AFFAIRS ARE IN A\nsnarl, consult FIDELITY CASH PROCURING\nA DEBT ADJUSTING SERVICE, *l7 Insur\nanea Bulldlne. ISth at Eye. 38*\nALLIED VAN LINE SERVICE.\n,,tl WAI^*I>^lSfmR.N n LOADS Vlnr\nProm SPRINGFIELD. MASS NOV. 3rd\nprom NEW YORK CITY NOV. 4th\nProm BOSTON NOV. 4th\nTo PITTSBURGH OCT. *Bth\nTO NEW YORK CITY OCT *lst\nUNITED STATES STORAGE CO.. INC.,\nfit 10th St. N.W. Metropolitan 1848.\nHollywood Orchard\nOut Georgia avenue, 3 miles past D. C.\nMae. Delicious cider, 40c saUon. Brins\ncontainer, 36*\nApples\u2014Sweet Cider\nRockville Fruit Farm\nThousands of bushels of Btaymen Wine\nsap. Grimes Oolden and York Imperial ap-\nSat low price. Cider made from clean,\n-pickad apples. Drive to Rockville,\nthen I mile out on road to Potomac,\nhona Rockville 44-M. Open dally nntU\nL\nMoving to Another City?\nOver *OO vans coverlns all parts of the\nUnited States, full or part load, and return\nload rates, over nlsht service to New York\nCity. _\nGuaranty Storage Company,lnc.,\nallied. Van Line Service.\nSouth Cjpitol A D Sis. Atlantic 2100\nPr in ti n g Craftsmen...\nare at your service for\nresult-getting publicity\nThe National Capital Press\n\"ftw&rjg- ww Phon\nROOF PAINTING\nMot a Job for amateur*. Let practi\ncal roofers make needed repair* end\napply genuine roof paint\u2014see the\ndi (Terence. Get our estimate.\nITfYIMQ Roofing 11# 3rd St. IW.\niVvA/lvO Company District 08**\nW Ashevufe\nflit. O.), points South. Lonc-alftance mov\n'ransfer Storsge\nLABOR MAY DECIDE\nRACE IN BAY STATE\nButler and Coolidge Center\nEfforts on Workers in\nSenate Contest.\n(Continued From First\npossible for the mills of the South to\ncompete on unfair terms with the\nMassachusetts mills.\nHe proposes, he says, to \"equalize\nthe hours of labor,\u201d throughout the\ncountry by the passage of a national\n48-hour law, which would Eerve as a\nprotection to the workers of Massa\nchusetts against unemployment. If\nsuch a law can be made to \u201cstick\u201d\nwithout a constitutional amendment,\nButler is for the passage of the law.\nIf it is necessary to go further and\nput through an amendment to the\nConstitution, he will support such a\nmove.\nThe Butler Campaign Committee is\ncirculating as part of its literature a\nleaflet issued by a railroad operating\nthrough the Democratic States of the\nSouth, which was distributed iif\nMassachusetts originally to induce\ntextile mill operators to move their\nplants South. The circular put out\nby ihe railroad was entitled: \u201cNo\nRestrictions,\u201d and it set out to prove\nthat mill owners would not be\nhampered by the laws affecting mill\noperation m Massachusetts, designed\nto protect the workers, if they moved\nSouth.\nThe Georgia laws were shown to be\nthe most \u201cfavorable\u201d of any Southern\nState. They allow a possible 60 hours\nper week for the women and children\nwho work in the mills, as compared to\nMasachusetts\u2019 48. The circular showed\nthat Massachusetts has 17 laws affect\ning labor in textile mills and that\nGeorgia and Alabama have only 4;\nNorth Carolina and South Carolina 5\nand Virginia 6. On the other hand the\nNorthern and Eastern States, in addi\ntion to Massachusetts, have anywhere I\nfrom 10 to 14 such laws.\nComparison of Wages.\nThe Massachusetts scale of wages\nper week of 48 hours in these textile\nmills is given at $lB, while the high\nSouthern wage is $14.75 and the ave-.\nrage $13.25. The circular adds: \u201cThe\nunion organiser has a hard time of it\namong the Southern textile operatives.\nMany times he has had to flee to es\ncape rough handling by thcwe sought to\n\u2018Join up.\u2019 Workers in Southern mills\nknow the boss as a friend.\u201d\nWhile Eben 8. Draper, wet million\naire Republican, was seeking the sena\ntorial nomination against Butler, with\nliquor as his chief issue, Butler kept\nhammering away at his 48-hour week\nfor mill operatives and other workers\nand kept insisting that what was need\ned was better business and more of it\nfor Massachusetts Instead of more\nliquor. In the end, despite the heavy\nwet sentiment in Massachusetts. Butler\nwon the nomination, though by only\n7,000 votes margin.\nIt was noticeable, however, that But\nler carried all the mill towns against\nDraper, although the sentiment in those\ntowns has been quite wet. Furthermore,\nButler had a majority of the vote in\nBoston, which has one of the wettest\nreputations among the cities of\nAmerica.\nIt would appear, therefore, that the\nButler campaign for better working con\nditions and a fairer show for the work\ners of Massachusetts in competition\nwith the workers in the mills of other\nStates has had some effect.\nAttack mi Labor Records.\nEach senatorial candidate is attack\ning the labor record of the other, as\nan employer of labor. Coolklge goes\nfurther and insists that Butler\u2019s record\non labor legislation while he was a\nmember of the State Legislature was\n\"bad,\" to say the least. This Butler\ndenies and his campaign committee has\nproduced the record of his votes on\nseveral measures that affected labor.\nThe Butler campaigners are making\nmuch of the fact that Coolidge, after\nhe had made a fortune out of his Fitch\nburg machine works during the World\nWar, moved the principal part of these\nworks from Fitchburg to Seneca Falls,\nN. Y. By so doing, they aay, Mr. Cool\nidge has deprived Massachusetts work\ners of employment. They point out at\nthe same time that Mr. Butler, despite\nthe depression in the textile business in\nthis State, has kept his mills in this\nState, where he employs thousands of\nworkers.\nCoolidge, in his speeches, has taken\nto asking whether Butler has large in\nvestments in stocks and bonds of cor\nporations which have their plants out\nside of Massachusetts, apparently\nthinking in this way to offset the at\ntack made on himself for moving his\nplant to Seneca Falls.\nMassachusetts, largely an industrial\nState, has a great number of mill and\nfactory workers. The campaign waged\nby both Butter and Coolidge is to win\nthe votes of as many of these workers\nas they can.\nAs campaigners neither of the can\ndidates can be called a success. They\nare not spellbinders. Mr. Butler never\nhas had a reputation as an orator, but\nif Mr. Butler is no shining light aa a\nspeaker, neither is Marcus Coolidge.\nButler's whole effort is to appeal to\nthe worker on the side of better wages\nand more of them, more to eat and\nmore clothes. Coolidge, while he\nevinces the same strong desire to see\nthat the worker has more work and\nmore wages, is also trying to show the\nworker that he may have his wine and\nbeer along with these other benefits if\nhe will vote the Democratic ticket.\nThe wet issue has a strong appeal to\nmany of the mill hands and other\nworkers in this State who are of for\neign extraction. In these mill towns\nare found thousands of English, Ital\nians, French and Belgians, all of whom\nhave been disgruntled over the pro\nhibition laws.\nDeclares for Repeal.\nThe Democratic platform, on which\nCoolidge is standing, declares for repeal\nof the eighteenth amendment. It at\ntacks also the Volstead act and pledges\nthe party to the repeal of the \u201cbaby\nVolstead act,\u201d the State enforcement\nlaw. Mr. Coolidge earlier in the cam\npaign was only a 14 percenter; that is,\nhe wss willing to bring back beverages\nwhich contained 14 per cent of alcohoL\nBut now he appears to have gone the\nwhole route and to have accepted the\nplatform of his party.\nMr. Butler early in the primary cam\npaign came out for the retention of the\nState enforcement law and for the\neighteenth amendment. The Repub\nlican platform, however, adopted after\nMr. Butler was nominated in Septem\nber, undertakes to hold out a little hope\nto the Republicans who are wet in\nsentiment\u2014many of them in practice.\nAfter declaring for the enforcement of\nthe laws relating to liquor, the platform\nadds that the Republican party of Mas\nsachusetts agrees with President Hoover\nthat persons who do not believe in the\neighteenth amendment have a perfect\nright to seek to amend the Constitution,\nand that they \u2018\u2018are not subject to criti\ncism for asserting that right.\u201d\nThe platform goes further than that;\nit says that the President\u2019s Law En\nforcement Commission will enlighten\nthe country as to the real facts of the\nsituation and help to wiser judgment\nas to the course that should be fol\nlowed. And Anally the platform says;\n\u2018\u2018And we believe that any mandate\nof the people, when clearly registered\nin a manner provided by. law, should be\ncarried out.\u201d\nWhen it comes to economic ques\ntions, the two senatorial candidates\nprobably differ little fundamentally.\nThey have the same points of view.\nThe decision of the workers in this\nelection, however, is likely, to be in\nfluenced by the large anyent jf un-\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, OCTOBER 25. 1930.-\nORATORS WHO COMPETE IN WORLD CHAMPIONSHIP\nLeft to right: Edmund GulUon, Washington\u2019s own champion of the United States; Paul Leduc, champion of Canada; Jack Mallard German, champion es\nEngland, and Andre P. J. Fioux, champion of France.\njL- a w.\niV*\u2019 W sL M\nm, m M\nr ..vW' jr atom\nLeft to right: William Hayes, champion of Ireland; Javier Vivancos\u00df., champion of Mexico; Clemente Perei-Zanartn of Chile, champion of South America,\nand Heins Bockhaeker, champion of Germany.\nWIDOW IS BACKED\nFOR WINGO\u2019S SEAT\nArkansas Parties United by\nDeathbed Request of\nRepresentative.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLITTLE ROCK, Ark., October 25.\nParty lines were erased in Arkansas\ntoday as Democrats and Republicans\nunited in observance of the last wish\nof the late Representative Otis T.\nWingo to have his widow succeed him\nin the House of Representatives, where\nfor-18 years he represented the fourth\ndistrict.\nTwo letters, written a few hours be\nfore his death, in Baltimore, requested\nthat In event of his death Mrs. Wingo\nbe accorded the Democratic nomination\nfor both the unexpired and two-year\nterm.\nThe letters were made public last\nnight by Ira D. Dulaney of Ashdown, a\nlife-long friend. One was addressed to\nMr. Dulaney and the other to the\nDemocratic State Central Committee.\nRepublican leaders immediately an\nnounced Mrs. Wingo would be unop\nposed.\nThe respect accorded Mr. Wingo\u2019s\nwishes was made more evident through\na statement issued by Osro Cobb, secre\ntary of the Republican State Commit\ntee and friend of the Wingos.\nCobb said he was prepared to have\namendment of a bill pending before\nCongress to change the name of a\nproposed national park to Wingo Na\ntional Forest.\nIt was not known definitely if Mrs.\nWingo would accept the nomination,\nbut there seemed no doubt it would\nbe tendered her by Democratic State j\nCentral Committee at a meeting Mon\nday.\nMrs. Wingo during the past four\nyears in Washington has been her hus\nband\u2019s Inseparable companion and a\nfamiliar figure in committee rooms and\nin the House gallery. She also has\ntaken an active part in Arkansas\npolitics.\nShould Mrs. Wingo reach the House\nit would be the second time in two\nyears that the widow of an Arkansas\nRepresentative has become her hus\nband's successor. Mrs. Pearl Peden\nOldfield, now retiring from Congress as\nRepresentative from the second district,\nsucceeded her husband, the late W. A.\nOldfield, two years ago.\nLEWISTAKESNOTICE\nOF THOMPSON BOLT\nVerbal Clash With Mrs. McCor\nmick Called \u201cRevolt\u201d Against\nParty Leadership.\nBy th. Amoo.ted Pres*.\nCHICAGO, October 25.\u2014First public\nnotice of McCormick-Thompson dissen\nsion was taken by James Hamilton\nLewis, Democratic senatorial candidate,\nlast night.\nHe termed the verbal clashes be\ntween his Republican rival, Congress\nwoman Ruth Hanna McCormick, and\nMayor William Hale Thompson a \u201cre\nvolt\" against party leadership.\nDissemination of circulars among col\nored voters urging support for Lewis\nwas charged against the mayor by Mrs.\nMcCormick and met with an avowal\nof Thompson\u2019s opposition to her for\nthe Senate seat she is seeking in the\ncampaign.\nThe Republican county management,\nhowever, has announced its adherence\nto the McCormick cause despite the\nmayor's stand.\nSpeaking at a campaign meeting last\ni 'night, Lewis said: \u201cOh, Chicagoans,\namidst this confusing complication now\nput on in central circles of Repub\nlican revolt we ask: Where is one\npromise to reduce taxation, to provide\npermanent employment in Chicago to\nthose the national powers have put\nf down and out?\u201d\nCLUB STAGES PLAY\nChurch Oroup Presents \u201cThe Tryst\ning Place,\u201d In Parish Hall.\nThe Dramatic Club of St. Stephen\u2019s\nan dthe Incarnation Episcopal Church\ni gave a play, \"The Trysting Place,\u201d\nThursday night in the perish hall.\ni Among those taking part were Miss\nDoris Dyson, Miss Lucille Milne, Miss\nJudith Wood, John Brasel, Charles\nPentx, William Phillips and Wells\nl Blandford.\ni\nHeld on Bad Check Charge.\ni Robert Rogers, 25 years old, of\nPhiladelphia, was arrested here yes\nterday by Headquarters Detective\ni Clarence Talley and is being held for\nPennsylvania authorities on charges\nof giving worthless checks and\nfraudulent real estate operattoM.\nI Rogep wm ha returned\nWill Rogers\nSays:\nBEVERLY HILLS, Calif., October\n25;\u2014Every paper every morning tells\nof a big gathering and prominent\nmen who have spoken on \u201cbetter\ntimes.\u201d If\nchambers of\ncommerce give\nsome worker a\njob Instead of\nsome speaker a\ndinner there\nwould benoun\nemploy ment,\nthere has been\nmore \u201dop 11\nmlsm\u201d talked\nand less prac\nticed than at\nP\nany time during our history. Every\nmillionaire we have has offered a\nspeech Instead of keeping still and\noffering a job. Our optimism is all\nat a banquet table, where every\nbody there has more than they can\neat,\nG.Q.P.GOVERNMENT\nLAUDED DY MILLS\nUndersecretary of Treasury\nSays Administration Has\nKept Promises.\nBr the Associated Press.\nBOSTON, October 25\u2014Ogden L.\ni Mills, Undersecretary of the Treasury,\nIn a speech here last night said the ad\nministration of President Hoover had\ncarried through to completion the pro\ngram on which it was elected and had\nmet every situation with decision, cour\nage and sound judgment.\nSpeaking at a rally sponsored by the\nYoung Men\u2019s Republican Social League\nof Boston, Mills said. the Republican\nparty was returned to power by a large\nplurality, pledged to revise the tariff in\naccordance with protective principles\nand more specifically in the Interests\nof agriculture. \"The promise has been\nkept,\u201d he said.\nTariff Is Defended.\nReferring to the tariff rates. Mills\nsaid: \u201cIt can be taken for granted that\nevery tariff bill will contain a number\nof rates hard to Justify, the inevitable\nresult of a give-and-take process among\nlegislators, who are each anxious to\nprotect home Industries, and who are\nnothing if not human.\u201d\nHe favored a Tariff Commission com\nposed of trained, well quail fled and un\nbiased men. \u2018\u2018Let them in each\ninstance,\u201d he said, \u2018\u2018determine the facts,\nand based on those facts and the prin\nciples and rules laid down by the Con\ngress for their guidance, make their\nrecommendations to the President. Give\nhim the authority to make their recom\nmendations effective by proclamation.\u201d\nHoover Is Landed.\nHe declared the McNary-Haugen and\nthe export debenture plan to be un\nsound in theory and unworkable in\npractice.\nMills praised the initiative of Presi\ndent Hoover in the business depression.\nHe said that owing to the good judg\nment of the American people there was\nan Executive in the White House who\nhad the knowledge, vision and courage\nto act. \"not that he believed that the\nfull tide could be turned,\u201d he said, \u201cfor\nthe Government is powerless either to\nmanufacture prosperity or, by its own\nactions, to overcome economic adversi\nty, but he did believe that Government\nleadership and suggestions could play\na mighty part in enabling private initia\ntive and effort to alleviate conditions^\u201d\nGET-TOGETHER IS HELD\nBY ROYAL ARCANUM\nSpeeches and Entertainment Fea\nture Program of Insurance\nMen at Raleigh.\nThe first annual get-together of the\nRoyal Arcanum, an organization of in\nsurance men, was held at the Raleigh\nHotel last night, with speeches and en\ntertainment featuring the program.\nThe committee in charge were Joseph\nF. Brashears, Roy O. Klotz, Raymond\nThayer, B. W. Bolinger, H. A. Kulze,\nDewey L. Shaw, I. 8. Childs, Chris Cot\nton, Charles A. Bell, Stephen H. Talkes,\nFrank V. Marsh, Gordon King, A. C.\nGiles and A. L. Ebersole. Guests of\nhonor were Harold C. Knoeppel, su\npreme regent; Julius Levy, supreme\ncommitteeman, and Charles A. Bell,\ngrand regent.\nThose taking part in the entertain\nment program were Honey Dasell, Mil\ndred Miller, Doris Perry, Monica Dwyer,\nRobert Vernon, Raymond Thayer. The\nprogram was under the direction of\nLeroy H. Thayer, And the music was by\nRobert E. Quirk end his orchestra.\nG. 0. P. CONGRESS\nIS URGED BY DECK\nHoover Needs Co-operation\nDuring Depression is Rep\nresentative\u2019s Claim.\nA plea to the people to elect a Re\npublican Congress at the coming elec\ntions on November 4. to enable Presi\ndent Hoover to have legislative co-op\neration during the business depression,\nwas made by Representative Beck, Re\npublican of Pennsylvania, in a \"radio\u201d\naddress over the Columbia Broadcasting\nSystem last night.\nMr. Beck, a former solicitor general\nof the United States declared:\n\u201cAs long as the present world-wide\neconomic crisis lasts, it is of supreme\nImportance, if the machinery of Gov\nernment is to function, that the Presi\ndent shall have the co-operation of a\nCongress that will not obstruct his plans\nor defeat his purposes/\u2019\nAsserting that \u201cthe present world\nwide economic crisis is more acute than\nany similar crisis in the lives of any\none now in being,\u201d Beck added that to\ncondemn the Hoover administration\n\u201cfor the world panic is as insanely\nfoolish as it would be to attribute a\ncyclonic storm at sea to the captain\nof a ship.\u201d\n\u201cPosterity will look back with admira\ntion,\u201d he said, \u201cto the patient and\ncourageous leadership of our President\nin these trying times. So far as the\nExecutive could act under our form of\nGovernment, he has left nothing un\ndone to rally the disorganized forces\nof Industry.\n\u201cI have a reasonable confidence,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cthat if the American peo\nple have the wisdom to give him a Con\ngress that will fully co-operate with\nhim, he will not only lead us out the\npresent \u2018slough of despond,\u2019 but will\nImmeasurably advance us to the \u2018de\nlectable mountains\u2019 of a greater pros\nperity than America has ever hitherto\nenjoyed.\u201d\nSIO,OOO SUIT DEFEATED\nBY VETERANS\u2019 BUREAU\nFloyd Patterson Failed to Prove He\nWas Disabled, and Had Received\nTraining, Court Holds.\nThe United Btates Veterans* Bureau\nwon a suit yesterday in the District Su\npreme Court when Justice Frederick L.\nSiddons, in Circuit Division 1, directed\na jury to return a verdict in the bu\nreau\u2019s favor in a suit for SIO,OOO brought\nby Floyd Patterson, a World War vet\neran, who claimed to have been per\nmanently disabled.\nAt the request of Attorney Anabel\nHinder liter, who represented the Vet\nerans\u2019 Bureau, the court directed the\nverdict, and pointed out that Patterson\nhad been trained as a bookkeeper be\nfore entering the military service and\nsince his discharge, August 5, 1920, the\nGovernment had supplemented his\ntraining in vocational schools. The\nveteran had not proved, the court said,\nthat he was disabled and can earn a\ngood living if he Is inclined to do to, the\ncourt suggested.\nLOYALTY DAY PLANNED\nTakoma Dutheran Church- Will\nHave Observance Tomorrow.\n\u201cChurch Loyalty Sunday\u201d will be ob\nserved tomorrow at the Takoma Lu\ntheran Church. Special efforts are being\nmade to have every member present at\nli a.m. The pastor. Rev. R. G. Stein\nmeyer, has chosen for his theme \u201cAre\nWe Living in Ninevah Today? Are the\nConditions in Our Land and the World\nToday to Be Taken Merely aa a Matter\nof Course, or May God Be Speaking to\nHie People Today?\u201d At 8 p.m. a stere\nupticon lecture, \u201cThe Holy City,\u201d will\nbe presented. Ihe public in invited.\nThe pastor will deliver the sermon in\nthe afternoon at a service to be con\nducted in the Clarendon (Va.) Theater.\nDR. GOODELL PLANS VISIT\nFederal Council Representative to\nArrange Evangelism Program.\nDr. Charles L. Ooodell of the Federal\nCouncil of Churches will be In Wash\nington October 29 in the interest of\nevangelism. Arrangements for his visit\ninclude a dinner for pastors and other\nleaders at o\u2019clock and the public\nmeeting at 8 o\u2019clock at Calvary Baptist\nChurch. The Committee on Evangel\nism of the Federation of Churches is\nmaking these arrangements under the\ndirection of its chairman. Dr. Chestoen\nSmith, pastor of Hamline Methodist\nChurch.\nAll Interested In this subject are In\nvited to bear Dr. Goodell at the 8\no\u2019clock meeting. This will be held In\nREPUBLICAN FUNDS\nEXCEEDING RIVALS\u2019\nG. 0. P. Spending More Than\nFive Times as Much\nas Democrats.\nThe Republicans are spending more\nthan five times as much money as the\ni Democrats in the congressional eam\npaign, according to reports of respec\ntive committees filed with the clerk of\nthe House of Representatives for the\nperiod between September 1 and Oc\ntober 22.\nExpenditures of $30,915 by the Demo\ncratic National Committee were matched\nby $163,200 expended by the Republican\nCongressional Committee. Most of the\nRepublican funds were spent on behalf\nof the re-election of House members\nin the States of Ohio, Indiana, Missouri\nand Kentucky. The money came from\nthe Republican National Committee,\nwhich contributed a total of $221,500\nfor the year. Total expenditures of\nthe congressional committee for the\nyear were given as $201,440.\nContribution and Loan.\nThe report of James W. Gerard, I\ntreasurer for the Democratic National\nCommittee, showed the Democratic\ncongressional campaign chest was\nmade up of a SSOO contribution by John\nW. Davis, Democratic presidential nom\ninee in 1924, and a loan of $30,000\nfrom Chairman John J. Raskob. Vir\ntually all of the expenditures listed\nwere for the headquarters office ex\npenses.\nRaskob also was listed as contributing\nSI,OOO for the Democratic drive in the\nfirst Connecticut district, SI,OOO In the\nfirst Oregon district and SSOO In the\nthird Kentucky district.\nA deficit of $596,375 for the Demo\ncratic National Committee, mostly com\ning over from the 1928 presidential\ncampaign, was reported. Os this amount\n$375,000 is owed on a loan from the\nBankers\u2019 Trust Co. of New York and\n$220,000 on a loan from Raskob.\nDistribution of Funds.\nThe Republican Congressional Com\nmittee sent $12,500 into Ohio; $4,000\nfor the Republican congressional cam\npaign In Indiana; $7,000 to Missouri;\n$2,500 to Maryland; $4,000 to West\nVirginia; $3,000 to New York; $2,000\nto Massachusetts; $2,000 to Con\nnecticut; SI,OOO to Vermont; SSOO to\nNew Hampshire; $3,000 to North\nCarolina; SI,OOO to Tennessee; SI,OOO to\nAlabama, and SI,OOO to Florida.\nO\u2019N EIURALLYH ALLS\nDECLARED \u201cSTOLEN\u201d\nSupporter* of Independent Dry\nCharge Unfair Colored Sec\ntion Tactic*.\nBr th# Associated Pres*.\nCHICAGO, October 25.\u2014For the\nnonce, the political spotlight has cen\ntered upon the colored wards.\nSupporters of Lottie Holman O\u2019Neill,\nIndependent dry candidate for United\nStates Senator, accused her foes of\n\u201cstealing\u201d meeting halls in the colored\nSouth Side section in which Mrs. O\u2019Neill\nhad planned to hold meetings.\nMrs. Ida Wells Barnett, prominent\ncolored Republican worker, supporting\nthe Independent candidate, said she\nhad been \u201cunable to -obtain any hall\nor church for an O\u2019Neill rally.\u201d Bhe\nsaid upon one occasion she secured a\nhall, paid the rent, printed announce\nments and later received the rent money\nback again with the remark that the\nplace had been reserved by the Repub\nlican ward committeeman. Mrs. Bar\nnett\u2019s charge followed closely upon the\naction of Mayor William Hale Thomp\nson, Republican, in issuing a circular\naddressed to colored voters, urging\nthem to support the Democratic sena\ntorial nominee, former Senator James\nHamilton Lewis, and attacking Ruth\nHanna McCormick, Republican candi\ndate.\nEVANGELIST JEFFERS\nTO SPEAK TOMORROW\nEvangelist Joe Jeffers, who is con\nducting a tent meeting at Second and\nRhode Island avenue, will preach in the\nWisconsin Avenue Baptist Church,\nForty-second and Fessenden streets,\ntomorrow morning at 11 o\u2019clock.\nThe pastor, Rev. Clarence R. Fer\nguson, will preach, at the o'clock\nevening service on \u201cThe Prophet\nMlcah.\u201d\nBible School meets at 9:45 am.' The\ncradle roll department will meet with\nMrs. Edward J. Fox in a new room at\nthe church. The B. Y. P. U. Societies\nwill meet p.m.\nThe teaflgers and officers of the\nBible Schcxajpeefc at 7 pm. Wednesday.\nThe Bible \u00bbWdy aad prayer\nI\nSome Seats Available\nPersons who were unable to\nobtain tickets for the Interna\ntional Oratorical Contest finals\ntonight will be admitted to Con\nstitution Hall promptly at 7:45\no\u2019clock and will be privileged to\ntake any unoccupied seat with\nthe exception of the boxes.\nThe hall itself will be opened\nat 7:15 for ticket holders and\npersons having general admis\nsion passes may take their choice\nof seats not within the reserved\n\"teachers' section, excepting, of\ncourse, the boxes.\nHolders of teachers\u2019 section\ntickets are warned that reserva\ntions on that block of seats lapse\nat 7:45 o'clock.\nOnly box seat reservations will\nbe held Indefinitely.\nThe contest Itself begins\npromptly at 8 o'clock.\nDEMOCRATS TO WIN\nOHIO; SHOUSE SAYS\nHoover Campaign Promises\nUnfulfilled, Cleveland\nv Audience Told.\nV the Associated Press.\nCLEVELAND, October 25.\u2014The pre\ndiction that Ohio will go Democratic In\nthe coming congressional election was\nvoiced today by Jouett Shouse, chair\nman of the Democratic National Execu\ntive Committee, in an address before\nthe Cleveland City Club.\n\"The reason fen- this tremendous\nshift from 1928, when you gave Mr.\nHoover a majority of 800,000,\u2019\u2019 he said,\n\u2022Ts not difficult to see.\u201d\nThe President was elected, Bhouse\nasserted, \u201cbecause he wqs able to con\nvince the people of this country that\nhe could accomplish certain things\nwhich involved the welfare of every\nman, woman and child In the United\nStates.\n\u201cHis promises filled volumes,\u201d he con\ntinued. \u201cHis promises are so dispropor\ntionate to these that his party spokes\nmen are driven to listing the most\nroutine matters of Government in order\nto show something affirmative in his\nrecord.\n\u201cNot a single major promise of his\ncampaign has been fulfilled. He prom\nised you prosperity\u2014definitely, specifi\ncally and without any its, but* or per\nhapses. And there are more shut-down\nfactories, destitute farms and men walk\ning the streets in search of work than\nat any time in the Nation\u2019s history.\u201d\nBOY ORATORS VIE\nFOR WORLD TITLE\nIN CITY TONIGHT\n(Continued From First Page.)\nTelle*, Mexican Ambassador, will sit\nwith young Vivanco R.; Don Carlos O.\nDa villa, Chilean Ambassador, 7 will ac\ncompany Perez-Zanartu; Friedrich W.\nvon Prittwits und Gaffron, German\nAmbassador, will be the companion of\nyoung Bockhacker; Sir Ronald Lind\nsay, British Ambassador, will sit with\nJack German, and Michael Mac White,\nminister of the Irish Free State, will\nsupport\" Hayes with his presence. In\nthe absence of Ambassador Paul Clau\ndel, young Floux, France\u2019s orator, will\nlook to Pierre Henry de la Blanchetal,\nfirst secretary of the French embassy,\nfor encouragement,. Similarly because\nVincent Massey, Canadian Minister to\nthe United States, is absent, Hume\nWrong, counsellor and charge d'affaires,\nwill accompany Paul Leduc.\nMr. Mac White, the Irish Minister,\nI will deliver the address at the open\ning of the contest. He will foUga\nPresident Hoover, who will extend\ngreetings to the orators and the as\nsembly they will have created. The\nPresident will reach the stage promptly\nat 8 o\u2019clock, accompanied by Frank B.\nNoyes, president of The Evening Star\nCo. and chairman of the American\nPublishers\u2019 Committee of the oontest\norganization. Mr. Hoover will be pre\nsented by Randolph Leigh, director\ngeneral of the contest, and with thA\nfirst presidential word, the contest meet\nwill be on.\nWhen the judges reach a decision\nthrough their ballots, Fleming Newbold,\nbusiness manager of The Star, will an\nnounce the winner. Immediately Dr.\nCloyd Heck Marvin, president of George\nWashington University, will present the\nsilver cup, trophy of the oratorical\nchampionship, to the victor.\nMusic for the contest will be pro\nvided by the Tech Symphony of the\nMcKinley High School here under the\ndirection of Dore Waltern, faculty\nleader. The orchestra itself will Intro\nduce the orators by playing their re\nspective Rational anthems.\nArt Buying Made Easy.\nHANGCHOW (IP).\u2014' To facilitate buy\ning of art objects by tourists, a build\ning left over from the 1929 exposition\nhere has been converted into a spe\ncial shop and order place, with deliv\neries direct to hotels.\n1 1 11 1\nInspect Tonight or Sunday (1\n[1 DETACHED HOUSE |i\njl AT ROW HOUSE PRICES ii\n[j HOMES OF 100 NEW IDEAS [j\njj Nortl; UtoflhrtftgE |j\n1 20th and Quincy Sts. N.E. and 21st and Randolph j 2\n|J A Beautiful New Restricted Subdivision of j\nI j Over 100 Detached Brick Homes\n2 6,7 and 8 Rooms Attic Play Rooms j\nSI Colored Porcelain Pool Room for Adults j\nBath and Kitchen Garages (j\nFixtures Open Fireplaces\nWe Will Be Looking for You This Evening\nDrive out Rhode Island Avenue to 20th I j\nStreet N.E.\u2014then north to Quincy Street I j\n26 Built\u2014 2o Sold\nOpen and Lighted Until 9 O\u2019Clock P.M.\nHRJiowensteih^!\n1311 H STREET NORTHWEST\nA-3\nSTRONG OPPONENT\nFACES T. J. WALSH\nG. 0. P. Counting on Galen\nto Align Montana Behind\nAdministration.\nBr th. Associated Press.\nHELENA, Mont., October 25\u2014Mon\ntana must decide on November 4\nwhether it will retire to private life a\nman who for 18 years has been its\nrepresentative in the United Btates\nSenate and whose activities in and out\nof Congress have brought him and the\nState Into marked prominence.\nThomas J. Walsh, one of the Senate\u2019s\noutstanding Democrats, and Its prose\ncutor In the now historic oil funds in\nvestigation. Is opposed for re-election by\nJustice Albert J. Galen, brought forth\nby the Republican organization in an\nasserted effort to align the State be\nhind the national administration.\nThree times Walsh has been charged\nby the citizens of Montana with rep\nresenting them in the United States\nBenate\u2014each time by a highly com\nplimentary majority. But Galen, too,\nhas found favor with these same voters.\nAn affable, rugged native son, who\ngrew up on a cattle ranch, Galen first\nentered the State\u2019s service as attorney\ngeneral. During the war he served as\na member of the Judge Advocate Gen\neral\u2019s Staff, in Siberia, with the rank\nof colonel. Returning, he was elevated\nto the State Supreme Court, where he\nIs serving a second term.\nState Net Party Bound.\nMontana is not party-bound. The\nfact that a large majority of its offi\ncers are Republicans has not prevented\nfrequent choice of a Democrat for Gov\nernor and the election of Democrats\nto three of Its four congressional po\nsitions.\nA Senator, two Representatives, a\nJustice of the Supreme Court, members\nof the Legislature and county officers\nwill be chosen.\nThe Democrat, Representative John\nM. Evans, and his Republican colleague.\nScott Leavitt, are actively opposed.\nMark D. Fitzgerald, dairy stock breeder,\nand fanners\u2019 00-operative leader. Re-\nGblican candidate in the first district.\nit his initial tilt with the veteran\nEvans two years ago. Tom stout, pub\nlisher of the Lewiston Democrat-News,\nmember of the 81xty-third and Sixty\nfourth Congresses, seeks Leavitt\u2019s place.\nCampaign discussions seem to have\nlabeled the Republican ticket as wet,\nwhile the well known dry sympathies\nof Senator Walsh seem to designate his\nparty as dry.\nWalsh Avoids Dry Question.\nGalen has expressed himself in favor\nof controlled manufacture and sale of\nliquor. So has Fitzgerald. Leavitt is\nsilent on the subject. Walkh has avoided\nthe question during his campaign, but,\nduring the Summer, volunteered the\nstatement that he would not oppose a\nreferendum and would abide by Mon\ntana\u2019s vote thereon. This also is Evans\u2019\nposition, but he considers the people\nvoted wet when they repealed the State's\nprohibition code in 1926, and declined,\nin 1928, to restore it. stout is frankly\nwet. Neither party referred to the sub\nject in its platform.\nTariff and farm relief have been em\nphasized as issues. Democratic speakers\nhave seised on reduced mining activity,\nthe difficulty of marketing livestock and\nthe diminished grain prices as argu\nments against extension of further aid\nand comfort to the administration,\ni Republicans challenge the position of\nSenator Walsh in opposition to the\ntariff.\nThe Republican Senator, La Fo\u00dfette\nof Wisconsin, has indicated an Interest\nin the success of Walsh, to the extent\nof scheduling five campaign speeches In\nthe State.\nRegistration figures reveal a total al\nmost equal to that in 1924 and 1928,\npresidential years, when the State bat\ntles were most ardent and veteran\npolitical leaders profess never to have\nseen attendance at political meetings\nin an \u201coff year\u201d equal to that of the\npresent campaign.\nTHIEF GRABS PURSE\nWoman\u2019s Focketbook Found With\n55 Cents Removed.\nA young man accosted Mrs. Emma\nEubanks, 4823 Fifth street, in front of\n510 Newton street last night, matched\nher pocket book and quickly disappeared.\nPoliceman W. 8. Kelly of the tenth\nprecinct. Investigating, found the dis\ncarded purse. Its contents of 55 cents\nhad been removed.\nENVOY COMING HERE\nV. Envoy to Germany Contrib\nutes SB,OOO for Winter Relief,\nLOUISVILLE. Ky\u201e October 25 (F).\nThe family service organisation yes\nterday announced Frederic M. Sackett,\nAmbassador to Germany, and Mrs.\nSackett had contributed $2,000 toward\nWinter relief activities. The Ambas\nsador and his wife recently left Ken\ntucky for Washington on their return\nto Germany,","height":"25536","width":"19824"}}
